net.hudup.core.client

Class ServerStatusEvent

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.EventObject
      • net.hudup.core.client.ServerStatusEvent
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class ServerStatusEvent
extends java.util.EventObject
    Server represented by Server class has six statuses as follows:
    • "started": Server started. If server has just started right after calling Server#start(), it is in two statuses: "started" and "running".
    • "paused": Server paused. Server are currently in both "started" status and "paused" status.
    • "resumed": Server resumed. Server are currently in three statuses: "started", "resumed", and "running".
    • "stopped": Server stopped and so server is in "stopped" status.
    • "setconfig": Server is in setting its configuration. Sever must stop so that it can set its configuration. So server is now in two statuses: "stopped" and "setconfig".
    • "exit": Server exits and so server does not exist. Status "exit" is unreal.
    Some statuses are overlapped; for example, server is in status "paused" is also in status "started". When server changes its current status by calling methods such as Server#start(), Server#pause(), Server#resume(), Server#stop(), and Server#exit(). Methods such as Server#isStarted(), Server#isPaused(), and Server#isRunning() are used to query current status of server. Every time server change its current status, it notifies an event ServerStatusEvent to listeners that implement ServerStatusListener interface. As a convention, this ServerStatusEvent class is called server status event. Such listeners are called server status listeners, which must be registered with server by method #addStatusListener(ServerStatusListener) to receive server status events. A server status event is removed from server by calling #removeStatusListener(ServerStatusListener).
